@ENDNODE

@NODE GETTING_STARTED "Getting Started"
@PREV INTRODUCTION
@NEXT MAIN_WINDOW
@TOC MAIN

@{APEN 2}@{B}Getting Started@{UB}@{APEN 1}
===============

To get started with iTidy:

1. Double-click the iTidy icon on your Workbench desktop to launch it.

2. In the main window, click @{B}Browse...@{UB} and choose the folder (or whole
   partition) you want to tidy. The selected location will appear in the
   Folder Path display.

3. Pick how you want icons ordered using the @{B}Order@{UB} cycle gadget (Folders
   First, Files First, or Mixed).

4. If you want iTidy to process everything underneath the chosen folder
   as well, enable @{B}Cleanup subfolders@{UB}.

5. If you want more control over layout, window shape, and spacing,
   click @{B}Advanced...@{UB} to open the Advanced Settings window.

6. When you're ready, click @{B}Start@{UB}. iTidy will process the selected
   folder (and any subfolders, if enabled), arrange the icons, and
   resize drawer windows using your chosen settings.

7. If backups are enabled, iTidy will create a restore point before
   making changes. You can roll back later using @{B}Restore Backups...@{UB}.

@{B}Tip:@{UB} For your first run, try a small test folder so you can see what the
options do without touching a whole partition. If you've enabled backups,
you can always restore afterwards if you want to undo the changes.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------


@{"  Return to Contents  " LINK MAIN}

@ENDNODE

@NODE MAIN_WINDOW "Main Window"
@PREV GETTING_STARTED
@NEXT ADVANCED_SETTINGS
@TOC MAIN

@{APEN 2}@{B}Main Window@{UB}@{APEN 1}
===========

The main window is where you pick what to tidy and choose the basic
options. It's meant to make the common "tidy this folder" job quick,
without getting in the way.


@{APEN 2}FOLDER SECTION@{APEN 1}
--------------

- @{B}Folder Path:@{UB} Shows the Amiga path of the folder that will be processed
  (for example "SYS:", "Work:Projects", or "DH0:Games"). It's read-only
  and updates when you select a new folder.

- @{B}Browse... Button:@{UB} Opens a file requester so you can choose the folder
  you want to tidy. The requester only shows drawers (folders), not
  files. If you prefer, you can also type a path directly. The last
  selected path is remembered for the current session.


@{APEN 2}TIDY OPTIONS SECTION@{APEN 1}
--------------------

- @{B}Order:@{UB} Sets how icons are grouped and sorted in the window. The
  choices are Folders First, Files First, or Mixed.
  - @{I}Folders First:@{UI} Drawer icons are listed before file icons.
  - @{I}Files First:@{UI} File icons are listed before drawer icons.
  - @{I}Mixed:@{UI} Folders and files are sorted together by name.

- @{B}Cleanup subfolders:@{UB} If enabled, iTidy will recurse through all
  subfolders under the selected path. This is the option you'd use for
  tidying a whole partition or a large folder tree in one pass. On
  classic hardware, very large trees can take a while, so it's normal to
  start it and leave it running.

- @{B}Backup icons:@{UB} If enabled, iTidy creates an LhA archive of the relevant
  ".info" files before making changes. That gives you something to roll
  back to later using @{B}Restore Backups...@{UB} from the main window. This
  requires LhA to be available in "C:". (This backup is about
  icon/layout changes; Default Tool backups are handled separately when
  fixing default tools.)

- @{B}Position:@{UB} Controls where drawer windows end up after iTidy resizes
  them.
  - @{I}Center Screen:@{UI} Centres the window on the Workbench screen (default).
  - @{I}Keep Position:@{UI} Keeps the window at its current location.
  - @{I}Near Parent:@{UI} Places the window slightly down and right of the parent
    window (similar to how Workbench tends to cascade windows).
  - @{I}No Change:@{UI} Resizes the window but doesn't try to move it.


@{APEN 2}OTHER CONTROLS@{APEN 1}
--------------

- @{B}Start Button:@{UB} Begins processing using the current settings.

- @{B}Advanced...:@{UB} Opens the Advanced Settings window for more detailed
  control.


@{APEN 2}MENU OPTIONS@{APEN 1}
------------

The menu lets you save and load your settings:

- @{B}Load Settings:@{UB} Loads previously saved preferences for layout, sorting,
  and backup options.
- @{B}Save Settings:@{UB} Saves your current configuration so you can reuse it
  later.

This is handy if you want one setup for general Workbench use and another
for things like WHDLoad folders or archive dumps.


@{APEN 2}TIPS@{APEN 1}
----

- The main window is meant for quick "point it at a folder and tidy it"
  runs. If you need more control over layout and window sizing, use
  @{B}Advanced...@{UB}.
- All changes apply to the selected folder and (if enabled) everything
  underneath it.
- If you're experimenting, enable backups and start with a small test
  folder first.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------


@{"  Return to Contents  " LINK MAIN}

@ENDNODE

@NODE ADVANCED_SETTINGS "Advanced Settings"
@PREV MAIN_WINDOW
@NEXT DEFAULT_TOOL_ANALYSIS
@TOC MAIN

@{APEN 2}@{B}Advanced Settings@{UB}@{APEN 1}
=================

You can open this window via @{B}Advanced...@{UB} on the main window. These options
are there if you want a bit more control over how icons are laid out and
how drawer windows are sized.


@{APEN 2}LAYOUT ASPECT RATIO@{APEN 1}
-------------------

Sets the target width-to-height "shape" for drawer windows.

- @{I}Tall (0.75):@{UI} Very tall, narrow windows
- @{I}Square (1.0):@{UI} Roughly square windows
- @{I}Compact (1.3):@{UI} Slightly wider than tall
- @{I}Classic (1.6):@{UI} More traditional Workbench proportions
- @{I}Wide (2.0):@{UI} Wider windows (default)
- @{I}Ultrawide (2.4):@{UI} Very wide windows


@{APEN 2}OVERFLOW STRATEGY@{APEN 1}
-----------------

Controls what iTidy does when a drawer has more icons than comfortably fit
on screen.

- @{I}Expand Horizontally:@{UI} Adds more columns (you'll scroll left/right)
  (default)
- @{I}Expand Vertically:@{UI} Adds more rows (you'll scroll up/down)
- @{I}Expand Both:@{UI} Tries to balance expansion in both directions


@{APEN 2}ICON SPACING (X AND Y)@{APEN 1}
----------------------

Sets the horizontal and vertical gap between icons (0-20 pixels). The
default is 8 pixels in both directions. Lower values pack icons tighter;
higher values give things more breathing room.


@{APEN 2}ICONS PER ROW (MIN/MAX)@{APEN 1}
-----------------------

- @{B}Min:@{UB} The minimum number of columns (default: 2). This stops drawers
  turning into a single long vertical list.
- @{B}Max:@{UB} The maximum number of columns (only used when Auto Max is
  disabled).
- @{B}Auto Max Icons:@{UB} When enabled (default), iTidy works out a sensible
  maximum column count based on your screen width.


@{APEN 2}MAX WINDOW WIDTH@{APEN 1}
----------------

Limits how wide drawer windows are allowed to become, as a percentage of
the screen width (Auto, 30%, 50%, 70%, 90%, 100%). This only applies when
@{B}Auto Max Icons@{UB} is enabled.


@{APEN 2}ALIGN ICONS VERTICALLY@{APEN 1}
----------------------

Sets how icons are vertically aligned when a row contains icons of
different heights: @{I}Top@{UI}, @{I}Middle@{UI} (default), or @{I}Bottom@{UI}.


@{APEN 2}REVERSE SORT (Z->A)@{APEN 1}
-------------------

Reverses the current sort direction (for example Z->A, newest-first, or
largest-first depending on the sort mode).


@{APEN 2}OPTIMIZE COLUMN WIDTHS@{APEN 1}
----------------------

When enabled (default), each column is sized based on the widest icon in
that column rather than forcing every column to use the same width.


@{APEN 2}COLUMN LAYOUT (CENTERED)@{APEN 1}
------------------------

When enabled (default), icons are centered within their column rather than
being left-aligned.


@{APEN 2}SKIP HIDDEN FOLDERS@{APEN 1}
-------------------

When enabled (default), iTidy skips folders that don't have ".info" files
when doing recursive processing. This helps avoid pointless work when
you're running across large trees.


@{APEN 2}STRIP NEWICON BORDERS@{APEN 1}
---------------------

Removes borders from NewIcons during processing. This requires
icon.library v44+ (Workbench 3.5+). This change is permanent for the
affected icons, so if you might want to go back to the original look
later, enable icon backups first.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------


@{"  Return to Contents  " LINK MAIN}

@ENDNODE

@NODE DEFAULT_TOOL_ANALYSIS "Default Tool Analysis"
@PREV ADVANCED_SETTINGS
@NEXT RESTORING_BACKUPS
@TOC MAIN

@{APEN 2}@{B}Default Tool Analysis@{UB}@{APEN 1}
=====================

You can open this window via @{B}Fix Default Tools...@{UB} on the main window. It
scans WBPROJECT icons and helps you find (and fix) default tools that no
longer exist.


@{APEN 2}WHAT IS A DEFAULT TOOL?@{APEN 1}
-----------------------

On the Amiga, most data file icons have a "Default Tool" set - the program
Workbench runs when you double-click that icon. For example, a ".txt" icon
might have "SYS:Utilities/MultiView" as its default tool.

After copying icons between systems or extracting older archives, those
tool paths often don't match what's actually installed. When that happens
you'll see the familiar "Unable to open your tool" error.


@{APEN 2}USING THE SCANNER@{APEN 1}
-----------------

1. @{B}Select folder:@{UB} Click @{B}Browse...@{UB} and choose a folder to scan. Scanning
   is always recursive (it will include subfolders).
2. @{B}Scan:@{UB} Click @{B}Scan@{UB} to examine icons and check whether their default
   tools can be found.
3. @{B}Review:@{UB} The list shows each default tool that was found, how many
   icons reference it, and whether it exists.
4. @{B}Filter:@{UB} Use the cycle gadget to show All, Existing only, or Missing
   only.
5. @{B}Fix:@{UB} If a tool is missing, select it and use @{B}Replace Tool (Batch)@{UB} to
   update all icons that use it. If you only want to change one file,
   select that file and use @{B}Replace Tool (Single)@{UB}.


@{APEN 2}TOOL LIST COLUMNS@{APEN 1}
-----------------

- @{B}Tool:@{UB} The default tool path (for example "SYS:Tools/TextEdit")
- @{B}Files:@{UB} How many icons reference that tool
- @{B}Status:@{UB} EXISTS or MISSING


@{APEN 2}MENU OPTIONS@{APEN 1}
------------

- @{B}Project menu:@{UB} New, Open, Save, Save As, Close. Saving scan results can
  be handy when you're working with large drives that take a while to
  scan.
- @{B}File menu:@{UB} Export the tool list or a detailed per-file list to text
  files.


@{APEN 2}DEFAULT TOOL BACKUPS@{APEN 1}
--------------------

Before iTidy changes anything, it automatically saves the original default
tool values as small text backups. This backup system is separate from the
icon/layout backups used for tidying.

To undo default tool changes, use @{B}Restore Default Tools Backups...@{UB} from
within this window. (This only restores default tool settings - it won't
restore icon positions or window layouts.)


@{APEN 2}TECHNICAL NOTES@{APEN 1}
---------------

When validating tools, iTidy checks absolute paths directly. For simple
tool names like "MultiView", it searches the Amiga PATH (parsed from
"S:Startup-Sequence" and "S:User-Startup") to see if the tool can be found
there.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------


@{"  Return to Contents  " LINK MAIN}

@ENDNODE

@NODE RESTORING_BACKUPS "Restoring Backups"
@PREV DEFAULT_TOOL_ANALYSIS
@NEXT TIPS_TROUBLESHOOTING
@TOC MAIN

@{APEN 2}@{B}Restoring Backups@{UB}@{APEN 1}
=================

You can open this window via @{B}Restore Backups...@{UB} on the main window. It
restores icon positions and drawer/window layout information from the LhA
backup archives that iTidy created. This is only available if you
previously ran iTidy with @{B}Backup icons@{UB} enabled.

Note: this restores icon/layout backups only. If you're trying to undo
default tool changes, use @{B}Restore Default Tools Backups...@{UB} in the Fix
Default Tools window instead.


@{APEN 2}RUN LIST@{APEN 1}
--------

The top list shows previous backup runs:

- @{B}Run:@{UB} A simple run number (0001, 0002, etc.)
- @{B}Date/Time:@{UB} When the backup was created
- @{B}Folders:@{UB} How many folders were backed up
- @{B}Size:@{UB} Total size of the archives
- @{B}Status:@{UB} Complete or Incomplete

Click a run to select it and view its details.


@{APEN 2}DETAILS PANEL@{APEN 1}
-------------

Shows information about the selected run, including the source directory,
how many archives were created, total size, status, and where the backups
are stored.


@{APEN 2}CONTROLS@{APEN 1}
--------

- @{B}Restore window positions:@{UB} When enabled (default), iTidy also restores
  drawer window geometry (size and position). Depending on your setup,
  you may need to restart Workbench before everything visibly updates.


@{APEN 2}BUTTONS@{APEN 1}
-------

- @{B}Restore Run:@{UB} Extracts the archived ".info" files back to their
  original locations, restoring icon positions and (optionally) window
  geometry.
- @{B}Delete Run:@{UB} Permanently deletes the selected backup run. This can't be
  undone, so only delete runs you're sure you no longer need.
- @{B}View Folders...:@{UB} Shows the list of folders included in the selected
  run.
- @{B}Cancel:@{UB} Closes the window without making changes.


@{APEN 2}WHAT GETS RESTORED@{APEN 1}
------------------

- The ".info" files that were backed up
- Icon positions (X/Y coordinates)
- Window geometry (if enabled)
- Folder view mode settings


@{APEN 2}REQUIREMENTS@{APEN 1}
------------

- LhA must be installed in "C:"
- Backup archives are stored in "PROGDIR:Backups/"
- Enough free disk space to extract the archives

--------------------------------------------------------------------------


